                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>is left for her regularly at <persName>Mrs Cohens</persName><lb/> in\n                    <placeName>Philada</placeName>—so <persName>Mrs Cohen</persName> writes\n                her.<lb/> Now as she receives one from me—you<lb/> yourself having directed it on\n                some<lb/> occasions, there must be a mistake<lb/> here, which you will no doubt\n                rectify.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">As far as I have been able to learn<lb/> I regret to say our few who\n                buy prayer<lb/> books here are not likely to <add>?</add><lb/> the publication of\n                the Hebrew Edition of prayers<lb/> you propose. If those who pay $10 for a<lb/> set\n                of Hebrew are a class who would sooner<lb/> pay 8 more &amp; have a set of Hebrew\n                &amp; English<lb/> —while those who buy all Hebrew prefer<lb/> those famous 5 dollar\n                sets Feyertags<lb/> Gibethe den Sphaidim<add>?</add> published “Bey<lb/>\n                <persName>Auton Edlen vore Sch<add>?</add></persName> (may his shadow<lb/> never be\n                less—even if his paper &amp; print be<lb/> better.) This ever living house has\n                issued<lb/> more than one sugar paper edition of<lb/> prayers with (such!) spanish\n                or<lb/> rather Shponish. I once thought it<lb/> would do to print Hebrew daily\n                prayers and<lb/> spoke to you about it. But <persName>Bush's</persName><lb/>\n                <add>?</add>, and a very nice little one<lb/> printed in Amsterdam which Hazan<lb/>\n                <persName>Lyons</persName>\n                <sic>showd</sic> me when in <placeName>New York</placeName></p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p38c9rq44/canvas/p3"
                }
              ]
